# image.env — the one file you edit to change what this repo builds.
#
# Together with the `FROM` / `ARG UPSTREAM_*` block at the top of the
# Dockerfile and the `VERSION` file at the repo root, this is the
# complete definition of the image this template produces. Everything
# else (registry, push credentials, SBOM sinks, air-gap mirrors) is
# CI configuration, not per-image config.
#
# Fork this repo per image. Edit:
#   1. Dockerfile              — the FROM line / ARG UPSTREAM_TAG / LABELs
#   2. image.env  (this file)  — per-image behavior flags
#   3. VERSION                 — your internal semver
# That's it. No other file in the repo needs to change.
#
# build.sh sources this file before invoking `docker buildx build`.
# All values become build-args passed into the Dockerfile, so the
# conditional multi-stages (remediate-${REMEDIATE}, certs-${INJECT_CERTS})
# pick the right branch automatically.

# ── Required ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Name of the image as pushed to your registry. This is the FINAL
# segment of the push URL: ${PUSH_REGISTRY}/${PUSH_PROJECT}/${IMAGE_NAME}:<tag>.
# Usually matches the upstream image name but can differ (e.g. you're
# rebuilding "nginx" but pushing it as "nginx-hardened").
IMAGE_NAME="nginx"

# ── Enrichment flags ─────────────────────────────────────────────────

# CVE remediation: run `apk upgrade --no-cache` inside the image to
# patch OS-level vulnerabilities between upstream releases. Set to
# "false" for images where the base is already minimal (distroless,
# scratch, busybox) or where you can't hit your apk mirror.
REMEDIATE="true"

# CA certificate injection: copies every *.crt / *.pem file from the
# repo's certs/ directory into the image's trust store before any
# network-touching layer runs. Set to "true" if you inject a CA via
# the CA_CERT env var or drop files into certs/ locally.
# When CA_CERT is set at build time, build.sh auto-flips this to "true".
INJECT_CERTS="false"

# USER value to restore at the end of the build. During remediate /
# cert injection we run as root (needed for apk, chown, etc.). This
# is the UID/username the upstream image ran as — check with:
#   docker inspect <upstream> --format='{{.Config.User}}'
# For nginx, the upstream entrypoint runs as root so it can chown
# /var/run/nginx.pid, run envsubst, etc., then drops to the nginx
# user itself. Setting USER nginx here would break the entrypoint.
ORIGINAL_USER="root"
